'''David Raya Martín''' (born 15 September 1995) is a Spanish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]]. Known for his consistency, distribution, shot-stopping abilities, and box command, he is widely regarded as one of the best goalkeepers in the world.<ref>{{cite web |last=White |first=Mark |date=4 December 2024 |title=Ranked! The 10 best goalkeepers in the world |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-the-10-best-goalkeepers-in-the-world |access-date=19 December 2024 |website=FourFourTwo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=4 March 2020 |title=The 25 best goalkeepers in world football – ranked |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/best-goalkeepers-world-football-ranked |access-date=19 December 2024 |website=90 min |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Raya began his senior career in England with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. He made his professional breakthrough as part of the team that was promoted from [[EFL League One|League One]] in 2018. He transferred to [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in 2019 and was a part of the team that was promoted to the [[Premier League]] in 2021. In 2023, Raya joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], and has since gone onto win three consecutive [[Premier League Golden Glove]]s and his first Premier League title in 2026.

Raya made his international debut for Spain in 2022,<ref>{{cite web |last=Bloom |first=Ben |date=4 July 2024 |title=Golden Glove winner Raya's incredible rise to the top |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4018980 |access-date=2 April 2025 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> playing at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and winning [[UEFA Euro 2024]].

==Club career==
===Blackburn Rovers===
Born in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Raya began his career in his native Spain and combined [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeping]] with playing as an [[outfield player]] in [[futsal]].<ref name=":0">{{cite web |last=Marshall |first=Sam |date=15 August 2023 |title=The Long Read: David Raya |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/en/news/article/the-long-read-david-raya-630187 |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=Brentford FC |language=en-gb}}</ref> He later played youth football for [[UE Cornellà|Cornellà]], before moving to [[Football in England|England]] to join [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a scholarship in July 2012, aged 17.<ref>{{Cite web |title=List of Players Registered as Scholars in Accordance with Rule C.3 Between 01/07/2012 and 31/07/2012 |url=http://www.thefa.com/~/media/2FC380172F88401482C3994AF130D59B.ashx |url-status=dead |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=The Football Association |page=49 |archive-date=23 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023232130/http://www.thefa.com/~/media/2FC380172F88401482C3994AF130D59B.ashx }}</ref><ref name="RoversProfile">{{Cite web |title=David Raya |url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/teams/first-team/goalkeeper/david-raya-martin/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707175140/https://www.rovers.co.uk/teams/first-team/goalkeeper/david-raya-martin/ |archive-date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref> Two years earlier, the transfer of Hugo Fernández to [[Ewood Park]] had led to an agreement between the two clubs for Cornellà players to join Blackburn Rovers for trials.<ref name=":0" /> He progressed through the club's [[Blackburn Rovers F.C. Under-23s and Academy|academy]] and signed a professional contract on 26 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Raya pens pro deal |url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2014/february/raya-pens-pro-deal/ |access-date=25 April 2015 |website=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref> Raya gained his first senior experience with a four-month spell on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Conference Premier]] club [[Southport F.C.|Southport]] during the first half of the [[2014–15 Football Conference|2014–15]] season and made 24 appearances.<ref name="SignsBrentford">{{cite web |title=David Raya signs for Brentford |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/july/david-raya-signs/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220629043820/https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/july/david-raya-signs/ |archive-date=29 June 2022 |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> After his return to Ewood Park, he made two [[2014–15 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|late-season]] [[EFL Championship|Championship]] appearances and signed a new three-year contract in April 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hard work pays off for David |url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2015/april/hard-work-pays-off-for-david/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |website=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref><ref name="Soccerbase1415" />

Despite making just 13 appearances during the [[2015–16 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2015–16]] and [[2016–17 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2016–17]] seasons,<ref name="Soccerbase1516" /><ref name="Soccerbase1617" /> Raya was Rovers' second-choice goalkeeper behind [[Jason Steele (footballer)|Jason Steele]] and was a frequent member of the matchday squad.<ref name="RoversProfile" /><ref name="Soccerway" /> Rovers' relegation to [[EFL League One|League One]] at the end of the 2016–17 season saw Raya take over as the club's first-choice goalkeeper.<ref name="FCHD">{{Fchd|id=BLACKBUR|name=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=David Raya pens long-term Rovers deal |url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2018/february/another-new-contract-for-a-young-rover/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=Blackburn Rovers F.C.}}</ref> He made 47 appearances during the [[2017–18 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2017–18]] season and helped the club to automatic promotion straight back to the Championship.<ref name="FCHD" /><ref name="Soccerbase1718" /> He retained his place during [[2018–19 Blackburn Rovers F.C. season|2018–19]] and made 46 appearances during a season of consolidation in the Championship.<ref name="FCHD" /><ref name="Soccerbase1819" /> Raya departed Rovers in July 2019,<ref name="SignsBrentford" /> after making 108 appearances for the club.<ref>{{Soccerbase}}</ref>

===Brentford===
On 6 July 2019, Raya signed for Championship club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on a four-year contract for an undisclosed fee,<ref name="SignsBrentford" /><ref>{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=David Raya: Brentford sign Blackburn Rovers goalkeeper for undisclosed fee |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48894390 |access-date=2 April 2025 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> reported to be in the region of £3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=Blackburn Rovers goalkeeper David Raya completes Brentford move |url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/rovers/news/17753757.rovers-goalkeeper-david-raya-completes-brentford-move/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |work=Lancashire Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Raya's performances during the first half of the [[2019–20 Brentford F.C. season|2019–20]] season earned him a nomination for Goalkeeper of the Year at the 2020 London Football Awards and his 16 [[clean sheet]]s in league matches during the season saw him share the [[English Football League|EFL]] [[EFL Golden Glove|Golden Glove]] award with [[Bartosz Białkowski]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bees up for London Football Awards prizes |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/en/news/article/bees-up-for-london-football-awards-prizes-470210 |access-date=9 February 2020 |website=Brentford F.C. |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref name="EFLGoldenGlove">{{cite news |title=David Raya presented with EFL Golden Glove prize |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2020/july/david-raya-golden-glove/ |access-date=28 July 2020 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> Raya made 49 appearances during a season which ended with a 2–1 [[2020 EFL Championship play-off final|2020 Championship play-off final]] defeat to [[West London derby|West London rivals]] [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref name="Soccerbase1920" /><ref>{{cite news |date=4 August 2020 |title=Championship play-off final: Brentford 1–2 Fulham (AET) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53603848 |access-date=29 May 2021 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Injury and transfer speculation led to Raya being left out of head coach [[Thomas Frank (football manager)|Thomas Frank]]'s matchday squads during the [[2020–21 Brentford F.C. season|2020–21]] [[pre-season]] and early in the regular season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Ben |last2=Ames |first2=Nick |date=17 September 2020 |title=Brentford reject multiple bids from Arsenal for goalkeeper David Raya |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/sep/17/brentford-goalkeeper-arsenal-david-raya-transfer-window-bids-rejected |access-date=2 October 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Westbrook |first=Ian |date=12 September 2020 |title=Raya set for return to training, says Frank |url=https://www.westlondonsport.com/brentford/frank-on-raya-benrahmas-absence-jensen-injury-and-bees-defeat |access-date=2 October 2020 |website=West London Sport}}</ref><ref name="Soccerway" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Brentford 2 Oxford United 2 |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2020/september/match-report-for-brentford-vs-oxford-united-on-01-sep-20/ |access-date=2 October 2020 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Pre-season: Brentford 3–0 Derby County |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2020/august/report-brentford-v-derby-county/ |access-date=2 October 2020 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> After being reintegrated with two [[EFL Cup]] appearances and [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] the team in both matches,<ref name="Soccerbase2021" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Verrall |first=John |date=23 September 2020 |title=Club now give player captain's armband, after reports Arsenal have bid for him |url=https://www.hitc.com/club-now-give-player-captains-armband-after-reports-arsenal-have-bid-for-him/ |access-date=2 October 2020 |website=HITC |language=en-GB}}</ref> he signed a new four-year contract on 2 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |title=David Raya signs new long-term contract |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2020/october/david-raya-new-contract/ |access-date=2 October 2020 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> Raya finished the 2020–21 season with 48 appearances, 17 clean sheets and a promotion medal,<ref name="Soccerbase2021" /> earned with a 2–0 [[2021 EFL Championship play-off final|2021 Championship play-off final]] victory over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref name="2021playoffs">{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=Gareth |date=29 May 2021 |title=Brentford 2–0 Swansea City |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57215919 |access-date=29 May 2021}}</ref> In his growing role as a [[sweeper-keeper]], Raya attempted 300 more passes than any other Championship goalkeeper during the season.<ref name=":0" />

Raya began the [[2021–22 Brentford F.C. season|2021–22]] season as a starter in [[Premier League]] matches,<ref name="Soccerbase2122" /> before suffering a [[posterior cruciate ligament injury]] during a 2–1 defeat to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 24 October 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Raya sustains knee injury |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2021/october/david-raya-knee-injury/ |access-date=26 October 2021 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> He returned to outdoor training on 10 January 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Raya roars back in to training |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2022/january/david-raya-roars-back-in-to-training/ |access-date=12 January 2022 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> After a [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] [[Friendly match|friendly]] appearance on 1 February 2022,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bees beaten by Aston Villa in friendly |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2022/february/bees-beaten-by-aston-villa-in-friendly/ |access-date=1 February 2022 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> Raya made his return to competitive match play with a start in a 4–1 [[FA Cup]] fourth round defeat to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] four days later.<ref name="Soccerbase2122" /> He was ever-present until the end of the campaign and finished a mid-table season with 25 appearances.<ref name="Soccerbase2122" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Tables – Premier League – England – Results, fixtures, tables and news |url=https://int.soccerway.com/national/england/premier-league/20212022/regular-season/r63396/tables/ |access-date=22 May 2022 |website=Soccerway}}</ref>

Raya continued as a starter in league matches during the [[2022–23 Brentford F.C. season|2022–23]] season and his performances during an unbeaten January 2023 (during which Brentford challenged the [[Premier League#International competitions|European places]]) saw him nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award.<ref name="Soccerbase2223" /><ref name="RejectContract">{{cite news |title=Raya 'happy' despite rejecting new Brentford deals |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64593562 |access-date=10 February 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rashford voted EA SPORTS Player of the Month |url=http://www.premierleague.com/news/3042896 |access-date=10 February 2023 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> That same month, Raya rejected a second offer of a new contract.<ref name="RejectContract" /> He was a member of the club's leadership group during the 2022–23 season.<ref name="Harris">{{cite news |last=Harris |first=Jay |date=15 August 2023 |title=David Raya on uncertain Brentford future: 'I've turned down two contracts' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4248008/2023/02/26/david-raya-exclusive-interview-brentford-contract/ |access-date=14 May 2023 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Soccerbase2223" /> According to [[Opta Sports]], Raya led all goalkeepers for both saves (154) and save percentage (77%) in the [[2022–23 Premier League]], becoming the only goalkeeper to top both categories in a single campaign in the competition since stats started being tracked in 2003–04.<ref>{{cite tweet |author=OptaJoe |author-link=Opta Sports |user=OptaJoe |number=1691465652115263488 |date=15 August 2023 |title=1 – David Raya led all goalkeepers for both saves (154) and save percentage (77%) in the Premier League last season; he is the only goalkeeper to top both categories in a single campaign in the competition since this data is available (2003–04, minimum 10 starts). Obstacle. |access-date=18 October 2024}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
====2023–24 season====
[[File:RC Lens - Arsenal FC (03-10-2023) 21 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Raya with Arsenal in 2023]]
On 15 August 2023, Raya completed a season-long loan move to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],<ref>{{cite news |date=15 August 2023 |title=David Raya: Arsenal sign Spain goalkeeper on season-long loan from Brentford |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66512991 |access-date=15 August 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=15 August 2023 |title=Arsenal sign GK Raya in loan deal from Brentford |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/38163304/arsenal-sign-goalkeeper-david-raya-loan-deal-brentford |access-date=2 April 2025 |work=ESPN}}</ref> becoming the fifteenth player from Spain to represent Arsenal's first team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/quiz-name-every-spaniard-play-arsenal |title=Quiz: Name every Spaniard to play for Arsenal |last=James |first=Josh |date=4 July 2024 |website=Arsenal.com|publisher=Arsenal FC |access-date=4 July 2024 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240704165229/https://www.arsenal.com/news/quiz-name-every-spaniard-play-arsenal |archive-date=4 July 2024}}</ref> Arsenal paid £3&nbsp;million to complete the loan deal, which had a purchase option of £27&nbsp;million. As part of the deal, Raya signed a two-year contract extension with Brentford, which also included a club option for an additional 12 months.<ref name="Raya joined AFC SkySports">{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12936962/david-raya-brentford-goalkeeper-moves-to-arsenal-on-initial-3m-loan-with-27m-option-to-buy |title=David Raya: Brentford goalkeeper moves to Arsenal on initial £3m loan with £27m option to buy |date=15 August 2023 |website=[[Sky Sports]] |access-date=18 October 2024}}</ref><ref name="Raya joined AFC NYT">{{cite news |last1=Humayun |first1=Ali |last2=Burlaga |first2=Kate |date=15 August 2023 |title=Arsenal complete loan signing of David Raya from Brentford; deal structure, new contract explained |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4761602/2023/08/15/david-raya-arsenal-brentford-transfer-confirmed/ |access-date=18 October 2024 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 17 September, he made his debut as a starter for Arsenal against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]], replacing [[Aaron Ramsdale]] as Arsenal's starting goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jonathon |date=17 September 2023 |title=Team news: Raya makes debut against Everton |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/team-news-raya-makes-debut-against-everton |access-date=18 September 2023 |website=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref> Raya would later make his Arsenal home and [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut against [[PSV Eindhoven]] on 20 September, keeping a clean sheet as the Gunners ran out 4–0 winners.<ref>{{cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=20 September 2023 |title=Arsenal 4–0 PSV Eindhoven: Gunners mark Champions League return with perfect performance |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66870515 |access-date=21 September 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 24 September, Raya started in the first [[North London derby]] of the season against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and had a mixed performance.<ref>{{cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=22 September 2023 |title=Arsenal 2–2 Tottenham Hotspur: Son levels twice in thrilling north London derby draw |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66835402 |access-date=30 September 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Discussing Raya's replacement of Ramsdale as Arsenal's starting goalkeeper, ''[[BBC]]'' journalist [[Phil McNulty]] stated in November 2023 that manager [[Mikel Arteta]] had to "face inevitable scrutiny about whether he has also reduced Arsenal's effectiveness and fluency by applying a fix to something that was not broken."<ref>{{cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=4 November 2023 |title=Newcastle 1–0 Arsenal: 'Mikel Arteta must face scrutiny for trying to fix something not broken' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67324261 |access-date=5 November 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 12 March 2024, Raya saved two penalties in a penalty shootout win against [[FC Porto|Porto]] in the Champions League round of 16, helping Arsenal reach the quarter finals for the first time since 2010, which McNulty stated "settled all lingering arguments about his status as Arsenal's first-choice goalkeeper".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68538063 |title=Arsenal 1–0 Porto (Agg: 1–1, Arsenal win 4–2 on penalties) |last=McNulty |first=Phil |website=BBC Sport |date=12 March 2024 |access-date=12 March 2024}}</ref>

On 20 April, Raya kept a sixth consecutive away clean sheet in the Premier League, becoming the second goalkeeper in the competition's history to achieve this feat, after [[Edwin van der Sar]] did so in 2008–2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3971799 |title=Arsenal win at Wolves to return to TOP spot |date=20 April 2024 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=19 October 2024}}</ref> On 4 May, he was confirmed as the outright winner of the 2023–24 [[Premier League Golden Glove]], having kept the most clean sheets (16) of any goalkeeper in the season.<ref name="PLGoldenGlove"/> Raya became the third Arsenal goalkeeper to win the award, after [[Wojciech Szczęsny]] and [[Petr Čech]], and the third Spaniard to win the award, after [[Pepe Reina]] and [[David de Gea]].<ref name="PLGoldenGlove"/> Raya was later included in the [[Professional Footballers' Association|PFA]] [[PFA Team of the Year (2020s)#Premier League 5|Premier League Team of the Year]] for the season.<ref name="PFATOTY2324"/>

====2024–25 season====
On 4 July, he completed his permanent move to Arsenal by signing a long-term contract.<ref>{{cite web |date=4 July 2024 |title=David Raya joins us on a permanent deal |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/david-raya-joins-us-permanent-deal |access-date=4 July 2024 |website=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=de Roché |first=Art |date=4 July 2024 |title=David Raya joins Arsenal on permanent transfer from Brentford after loan spell |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5614086/2024/07/04/david-raya-arsenal-transfer-permanent/ |access-date=4 July 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=4 July 2024 |title=Arsenal complete GK Raya transfer after loan |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/40333563/arsenal-complete-david-raya-transfer-one-year-loan |access-date=2 April 2025 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> In the game against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 24 August, he made a one-handed stop to keep out [[Ollie Watkins]]'s close-range header,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/aston-villa-vs-arsenal/report/505817 |title=Aston Villa 0–2 Arsenal: Leandro Trossard and Thomas Partey on target as Gunners claim revenge |last=Wright |first=Nick |date=24 August 2024 |website=Sky Sports |access-date=25 August 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4090903 |title=Trossard stars off the bench to maintain winning start for Arsenal |date=24 August 2024 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=25 August 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2024-Aug-24/aston-villa-0-2-arsenal-match-report |title=Report: Aston Villa 0–2 Arsenal |last=James |first=Josh |date=24 August 2024 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=25 August 2024}}</ref> which was named that month's [[Premier League Save of the Month]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4110695 |title=Raya wins Premier League Save of the Month award |date=13 September 2024 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=13 September 2024}}</ref>

On 19 September, he saved a penalty against Italian side [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]] taken by [[Mateo Retegui]] and the rebound header, becoming the fourth Arsenal goalkeeper to save a penalty in the Champions League, after [[Richard Wright (footballer)|Richard Wright]], [[Jens Lehmann]] and [[Łukasz Fabiański]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jonathon |date=19 September 2024 |title=Report: Atalanta 0–0 Arsenal |url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2024-Sep-19/atalanta-0-0-arsenal-match-report |access-date=20 September 2024 |website=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Opta Analyst |author-link=Opta Sports |date=19 September 2024 |title=Atalanta 0–0 Arsenal Stats: David Raya the Hero for Disappointing Gunners |url=https://theanalyst.com/2024/09/atalanta-vs-arsenal-stats-champions-league-live |access-date=20 September 2024 |website=The Analyst}}</ref> In his post-match interview, Raya credited Arsenal's goalkeeping coach [[Iñaki Caña]] for the role he played in his double save against Atalanta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rampling |first=Ali |date=19 September 2024 |title=David Raya credits Arsenal goalkeeper coach Inaki Cana after Atalanta double-save |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5780575/2024/09/19/david-raya-penalty-save-champions-league/ |access-date=20 September 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Collings |first=Simon |date=19 September 2024 |title=David Raya reveals Inaki Cana conversation before stunning Arsenal save |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/raya-save-inaki-cana-arsenal-fc-champions-league-2024-b1183071.html |access-date=20 September 2024 |website=[[Evening Standard]]}}</ref> He was later voted as Arsenal's Player of the Month for September.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jonathon |date=9 October 2024 |title=Raya named September's men's Player of the Month |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/raya-named-septembers-mens-player-month |access-date=19 October 2024 |website=Arsenal FC}}</ref> On 27 December, Raya claimed a clean sheet against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], his 23rd clean sheet in 50 Premier League games for Arsenal. In doing so, Raya broke [[David Seaman]]'s record (22) set in 1993 for the most clean sheets kept by an Arsenal goalkeeper in his first 50 Premier League appearances.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal go second and cut Liverpool's lead to six points |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4205251 |date=27 December 2024 |access-date=28 December 2024 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Critchlow |first=Dan |date=29 December 2024 |title=David Raya explains turning point as he breaks Arsenal club record |url=https://dailycannon.com/2024/12/david-raya-arsenal-record/ |access-date=29 December 2024 |website=DailyCannon |language=en-US}}</ref> Raya went onto secure his second consecutive Premier League Golden Glove, sharing the award with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] goalkeeper [[Matz Sels]], after both kept 13 clean sheets.<ref>{{cite web |date=25 May 2025 |title=Raya and Sels share Premier League Golden Glove award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4316253 |access-date=28 May 2025 |publisher=[[Premier League]]}}</ref>

====2025–26 season====

On 13 September 2025, Raya made his 100th appearance for Arsenal in a 3–0 home win against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], also recording his 42nd clean sheet for the club.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stephen |first=Wright|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/raya-100-apps-zubimendi-and-ucl-targets |title=Raya on 100 apps, Zubimendi and UCL targets |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=16 Sep 2025}}</ref> Later that year, on 4 November, Raya recorded a joint club-record eighth consecutive clean sheet and his 50th clean sheet overall in his 110th appearance for Arsenal during a 3–0 away victory over [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]], surpassing the mark previously set by [[Jimmy Ashcroft]], who reached the milestone in 114 matches in 1903.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rogers |first=Jonathon |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/club-clean-sheet-record-equalled-whats-next |title=Club clean sheet record equalled, but what's next? |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=5 November 2025 }}</ref>

On 4 May 2026, after his only challenger [[Gianluigi Donnarumma]] conceded against Everton, Raya was confirmed as at least a partial (later outright) winner of the 2025–26 Premier League Golden Glove, becoming only the fourth ever goalkeeper to win the award in three successive seasons, after [[Pepe Reina]] (Liverpool), [[Joe Hart]] (Man City) and [[Ederson (footballer, born 1993)|Ederson]] (Man City).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4604681 |title=Raya wins at least a share of Coca-Cola Golden Glove award |website=premierleague.com |date=4 May 2026}}</ref> A day later, he kept his 9th clean sheet in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] in a 1–0 victory over [[Atlético Madrid]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|semi-final]] second leg, equaling the competition's record set by [[Sebastiano Rossi]], [[Santiago Cañizares]], [[Keylor Navas]] and [[Édouard Mendy]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Peat |first=Charlie |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/clean-sheet-record-inspiring-our-ucl-journey |title=The clean sheet record inspiring our UCL journey |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=6 May 2026 }}</ref> A few weeks later, on 18 May, he recorded his 19th league clean sheet in a 1–0 victory over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], equaling the club record set by [[David Seaman]] in the 1993–94 and 1998–99 seasons.<ref>{{cite web |last=Knapton |first=Ben |url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/arsenal/title-race/news/saka-emulates-henry-as-arsenal-equal-two-pl-records-in-burnley-success_597793.html |title=Arsenal equal two Premier League records as Bukayo Saka emulates Thierry Henry in Burnley victory |publisher=Sports Mole |date=18 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
After failing to receive a call-up by [[Spain national football team|Spain]] at youth level,<ref>{{cite news |last=Bosher |first=Luke |date=31 August 2022 |title=Manchester United's David de Gea left out of Spain squad with Brentford's David Raya included instead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4181164/2022/03/18/manchester-uniteds-david-de-gea-left-out-of-spain-squad-with-brentfords-david-raya-included-instead/ |access-date=18 March 2022 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Raya won his maiden international call-up to the senior team for a pair of friendlies in March 2022.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |title=Raya in Spain squad |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/en/news/article/david-raya-in-spain-squad-2022-fifa-world-cup |access-date=11 November 2022 |website=Brentford F.C. |language=en-gb}}</ref> He made his debut with a start in a 2–1 win over [[Albania national football team|Albania]] on 26 March and remained an unused substitute in the second match.<ref name=":1" /> Raya was an unused substitute during the entirety of Spain's victorious [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League A|2022–23 UEFA Nations League]] campaign.<ref name="Soccerway" /><ref name="UNLWin">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Emma |title=Spain win Nations League final on penalties |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65944659 |access-date=18 June 2023 |date=18 June 2023 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref>

Raya was named in Spain's [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] squad,<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{cite web |date=11 November 2022 |title=Luis Enrique names Spain's 2022 World Cup squad: Ansu Fati is not missing out |url=https://www.marca.com/en/world-cup/2022/11/11/636e4059e2704efd988b45db.html |access-date=2 April 2025 |website=Marca|location=Spain}}</ref> but prior to the team's exit in the round of 16,<ref>{{cite news |last=Hafez |first=Shamoon |date=5 December 2022 |title=World Cup 2022: Morocco 0–0 Spain (3–0 pens) Achraf Hakimi chips winning penalty to reach quarters |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63789751 |access-date=6 December 2022 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> his only match play during the period came with a second half substitute appearance in a pre-tournament friendly versus [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]].<ref name="NFT" />

He was part of the Spain squad that won [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref name=":2">{{cite web |date=14 July 2024 |title=David Raya wins Euro 2024 with Spain |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/raya-wins-euro-2024-spain |access-date=15 July 2024 |website=[[Arsenal F.C.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=27 May 2024 |title=Euro 2024: Rodri and Cucurella in provisional Spain squad |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c199jjjg9y3o |access-date=2 April 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He played only one match, starting the final group stage match in a 1–0 win over Albania.<ref name=":2" />

==Style of play==
A [[sweeper-keeper]], Raya "is renowned as a vocal keeper, as well as one who is adept with the ball at his feet".<ref name="Nash">{{Cite web |last=Nash |first=Matthew |date=20 August 2021 |title=David Raya predicts more Premier League scalps for Brentford after Arsenal upset |url=https://metro.co.uk/2021/08/20/brentfords-david-raya-predicts-more-premier-league-scalps-after-arsenal-win-15122709/ |access-date=23 August 2021 |website=Metro |language=en}}</ref> He "can play out from the back and is happy covering the space in behind", which allows a team "to play with a high line".<ref name="SignsBrentford" /> As a result of his and Brentford's style of play during the [[2020–21 EFL Championship|2020–21]] season, Raya attempted 300 more passes than any other goalkeeper in the Championship.<ref name="Nash" />

In an exclusive interview with [[Sky Sports]] on 14 August 2024, Raya credited former Brentford and current Arsenal goalkeeping coach [[Iñaki Caña]] – who was a key figure in Raya's transfer from Blackburn to Brentford in 2019 and his move from Brentford to Arsenal in 2023<ref name="Raya joined AFC SkySports"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4777167/2023/08/15/raya-arsenal-brentford-rise/ |title=The rise of David Raya: To Arsenal via Brentford, Barcelona and Blackburn |last=Harris |first=Jay |date=15 August 2023 |website=The New York Times |access-date=18 October 2024}}</ref> – for transforming the way he played.<ref name="exclusive interview SkySports">{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/13196054/david-raya-exclusive-interview-arsenals-master-of-proactive-goalkeeping-ready-to-go-again-after-amazing-year |title=David Raya exclusive interview: Arsenal's master of 'proactive' goalkeeping ready to go again after 'amazing' year |last=Wright |first=Nick |date=14 August 2024 |website=Sky Sports |access-date=18 October 2024}}</ref><ref name="exclusive interview SkySports YouTube">{{cite AV media |date=14 August 2024 |title="It's a pleasure to be a part of this club" {{pipe}} David Raya reflects on the past year |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d32o9jMTSNg |access-date=18 October 2024 |website=Sky Sports Premier League |via=YouTube}}</ref>

{{Blockquote
| text=
"At Blackburn, [I was] just waiting to make saves. When I signed for Brentford, Iñaki completely changed my style of being a goalkeeper, to be more proactive and anticipate stuff... [If] you can go for a cross, go for it. Don't [just] wait for the save. For balls in behind, stay high to be able to cut out the attack... At Brentford and [Arsenal], my numbers on crosses are remarkable. I love it. [Being an] extra player to get that security straight from the back. I love being part of the build-up [and] trying to create goals and attacks... The benefit is bigger than the risk."
| author=David Raya speaking to Sky Sports on 14 August 2024<ref name="exclusive interview SkySports"/><ref name="exclusive interview SkySports YouTube"/>
}}

==Personal life==
Raya grew up in [[Pallejà]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Get to Know: David Raya |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/july/david-raya-10-things/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220716122504/https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/july/david-raya-10-things/ |archive-date=16 July 2022 |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=Brentford F.C.}}</ref> In July 2025, he married Tatiana Trouboul.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-07-06 |title=De los dos impresionantes vestidos de novia a la actuación de Omar Montes: Las imágenes de la boda del futbolista David Raya y la modelo Tatiana Trouboul |url=https://www.lecturas.com/actualidad/dos-impresionantes-vestidos-novia-actuacion-omar-montes-imagenes-boda-futbolista-david-raya-modelo-tatiana-trouboul_177944 |access-date=2025-07-11 |website=Lecturas |language=es}}</ref>

